The paper deals with the complexity of control attacks on elections, which is a topic that falls under computational social choice (cs.GT) and algorithmic game theory (cs.GT). The paper also involves the study of election systems and their winner problems, which is related to data structures (cs.DS). The use of algorithms to manipulate elections and the analysis of their complexity falls under artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper discusses the order of play and its influence on the complexity, which is a topic in computational complexity theory (cs.CC).
